b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe15066.htm)  [Next](sbe15068.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B002DEMBWG/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Upanishads, Part 2 (SBE15)_ , by Max Muller, [1879], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### FOURTH BR\xc3\x82HMA _N_ A 2.\n\n1\\. Then Ushasta Kakraya _n_ a asked. 'Ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya,' he said, 'tell me\nthe Brahman which is visible, not invisible 3, the Self (atman), who is within\nall.'\n\nYa _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya replied: 'This, thy Self, who is within all.'\n\n'Which Self, O Ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya, is within all?'\n\nYa _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya replied: 'He who breathes in the up-breathing, he is thy\nSelf, and within all. He who breathes in the down-breathing, he is thy Self,\nand within all. He who breathes in the on-breathing, he is thy Self, and\nwithin all. He who breathes in\n\np. 129\n\nthe out-breathing, he is thy Self, and within all. This is thy Self, who is\nwithin all.'\n\n2\\. Ushasta Kakraya _n_ a said: 'As one might say, this is a cow, this is a\nhorse, thus has this been explained by thee. Tell me the Brahman which is\nvisible, not invisible, the Self, who is within all.'\n\nYa _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya replied: 'This, thy Self, who is within all.'\n\n'Which Self, O Ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya, is within all?'\n\nYa _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya replied: 'Thou couldst not see the (true) seer of sight,\nthou couldst not hear the (true) hearer of hearing, nor perceive the perceiver\nof perception, nor know the knower of knowledge. This is thy Self, who is\nwithin all. Everything also is of evil.' After that Ushasta Kakraya _n_ a held\nhis peace.\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[128:2](sbe15067.htm#fr_401) Madhyandina text, p. 1071. It follows after what\nis here the fifth Brahma _n_ a, treating of Kaho _d_ a Kaushitakeya.\n\n[128:3](sbe15067.htm#fr_402) Deussen, Vedanta, p. 163, translates, 'das\nimmanente, nicht transcendente Brahman,' which is right, but too modern.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: III, 5](sbe15068.htm)\n\n"